%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Relationship between device-level and economy-wide rebound}
\label{sec:relationship}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

Device-level rebound~($Re_{dev}$) can be expressed as
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:dev_level_rebound}
  Re_{dev} = 1 - \frac{E_{sav,dev}}{E_{sav,dev,expected}} \; ,
\end{equation}
%
where $E_{sav,dev}$ is the actual device-level energy savings (in kW-hr)
over the life of the device, and
$E_{sav,dev,expected}$ is the expected device-level energy savings (in kW-hr)
over the life of the device.

Some of the expected device-level energy savings can be ``taken back'' by 
device-level rebound effects~($Re_{dev}$).
Expected device-level energy savings~($E_{sav,dev,expected}$) 
can be expressed in terms of device-level rebound~($Re_{dev}$)
by solving Eq.~\ref{eq:dev_level_rebound} for $E_{sav,dev,expected}$:
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:E_sav_dev_expected}
  E_{sav,dev,expected} = \frac{E_{sav,dev}}{1 - Re_{dev}} \; .
\end{equation}

To connect device-level rebound~($Re_{dev}$) to economy-wide rebound~($Re_{EW}$),
net cost savings at the device level~($C_{sav,dev,net}$) 
due to actual energy savings at the device level~($E_{sav,dev}$) 
are first determined by the following equation:
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:actual_cost_savings}
  C_{sav,dev,net} = E_{sav,dev} p_{E_f} - C_{install} \; ,
\end{equation}
%
where $p_{E_f}$ is the price of final energy purchased by the consumer (in \$/kW-hr, for example), and
$C_{install}$ is the cost of installing the energy-saving device,
including labor and materials (in \$).

But the net cost savings at the device level~($C_{sav,dev,net}$, in \$)
is freed cash 
which can be re-spent in the economy,
spinning through it similar to how a tax cut generates additional GDP.
Exactly how much economic growth is created by the freed cash of the 
net, device-level energy cost savings 
depends on how much of the savings are re-spent by consumers.
The term for the respending fraction is ``marginal propensity to consume''~($\mpc$).
(The value of $\mpc$ is between 0 and 1, 
with 0 representing no respending and 1 representing full respending.)

A multiplier~($k$) can be used to describe the infinite series of respending in the economy.
(Generating additional economic activity from a tax cut or other savings 
is known as the ``multiplier effect.'')
The multiplier~($k$) is related to $\mpc$ by 
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:k_eqn}
  k = \frac{1}{1 - \mpc} \; .
\end{equation}

Every new dollar spent in an economy,
including energy cost savings,
has energy implications.
On average,
the economy-wide primary energy implications of device-level energy cost savings 
can be estimated by the primary energy intensity of economic activity~($I_{E_p}$)
in units of kW-hr/\$.
Thus, the freed cash from 
net device-level energy cost saving~($C_{sav,dev,net}$) 
leads to new, economy-wide primary energy demand~($E_{nd,EW}$)
by the following equation:
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:E_nd_EW_prelim}
  E_{nd,EW} = C_{sav,dev,net} \; k \; I_{E_p} \; .
\end{equation}
%
Substituting Eq.~\ref{eq:actual_cost_savings} into Eq.~\ref{eq:E_nd_EW_prelim} gives
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:E_nd_EW}
  E_{nd,EW} = (E_{sav,dev} p_E - C_{install}) \; k \; I_{E_p}
\end{equation}

The net energy savings from the device-level energy savings is given by 
the difference between actual device-level energy savings~($E_{sav,dev}$) and
economy-wide new energy demand~($E_{nd,EW}$):
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:net_savings}
  E_{sav,net} = E_{sav,dev} - E_{nd,EW} \; .
\end{equation}
%
Substituting Eq.~\ref{eq:E_nd_EW} into Eq.~\ref{eq:net_savings} and rearranging gives
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:E_sav_net}
  E_{sav,net} = E_{sav,dev} \left[1 - \left(p_{E_f} - \frac{C_{install}}{E_{sav,dev}} \right) \; k \; I_{E_p} \right] \; .
\end{equation}
%
Note that $\frac{C_{install}}{E_{sav,dev}}$ is the unit cost to save energy 
(in \$/kW-hr, the same units as final energy price, $p_{E_f}$).

The economy-wide energy rebound effect~($Re_{EW}$) resulting from device-level energy saving
is given as 
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:Re_EW_prelim}
  Re_{EW} = 1 - \frac{E_{sav,net}}{E_{sav,dev,expected}} \; .
\end{equation}
%
Substituting Eqs.~\ref{eq:E_sav_dev_expected} and \ref{eq:E_sav_net} 
into Eq.~\ref{eq:Re_EW_prelim} gives
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:Re_EW_intermediate}
  Re_{EW} = 1 - \frac{E_{sav,dev} \left[1 - \left(p_{E_f} - \frac{C_{install}}{E_{sav,dev}} \right) \; k \; I_{E_p} \right]}
            {\frac{E_{sav,dev}}{1 - Re_{dev}}} \; .
\end{equation}
%
Simplification of Eq.~\ref{eq:Re_EW_intermediate} gives the final result
for economy-wide rebound~($Re_{EW}$):
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:Re_EW}
  Re_{EW} = 1 - (1 - k I_{E_p} P ) (1 - Re_{dev}) \; ,
\end{equation}
%
where $P = \left( p_{E_f} - \frac{C_{install}}{E_{sav,dev}} \right)$ is the device-level unit profit 
from an energy efficiency device
Eq.~\ref{eq:dev_level_rebound} can be solved for $E_{sav,dev}$ and
substituted to obtain
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:P_eqn}
  P =  p_{E_f} - \frac{C_{install}}{(1 - Re_{dev})E_{sav,dev,expected}} \; .
\end{equation}
%
Device-level rebound~($Re_{dev}$) is seen to reduce profit~($P$) to the device owner.

Eq.~\ref{eq:Re_EW} relates 
%
\begin{enumerate*}[label={(\alph*)}]
	
  \item device-level rebound~($Re_{dev}$) and
  
  \item economy-wide rebound~($Re_{EW}$).
    
\end{enumerate*}
% 
Key parameters in the relationship are 
%
\begin{enumerate*}[label={(\alph*)}]
	
  \item the multiplier~($k$) and the marginal propensity to consume~($\mpc$) 
        from which it is derived,
  
  \item the primary energy intensity of economic activity~($I_{E_p}$), and 
  
  \item the unit profit of energy efficiency~($P$).
    
\end{enumerate*}

The first derivative of economy-wide rebound with respect to device-level rebound
($\frac{\mathrm{d} Re_{EW}}{\mathrm{d} Re_{dev}}$) 
can be calculated from Eq.~\ref{eq:Re_EW}, and
it indicates how economy-wide rebound will change with device-level rebound:
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:dRe_EW/dRe_dev}
  \frac{\mathrm{d} Re_{EW}}{\mathrm{d} Re_{dev}} = 1 - k I_{E_p} p_{E_f} \; .
\end{equation}


