<<profit>>=
# From the LED packaging:
# Assumed electricity price (final energy)
p_E_f <- 0.11 # USD/kW-hr
# Cost savings claimed by manufacturer
C_sav <- 84 # USD
# Cost to purchase and install the LED bulb
C_install <- 1.5 # USD
# Expected device-level savings.
E_sav_dev_expected <- C_sav / p_E_f
# Unit profit
P <- p_E_f - C_install / ((1 - Re_dev) * E_sav_dev_expected)
@

**** The above \$ are 2019. 
Need to ensure that we're doing the right thing between 2019 and 2016 USD. ****

A visit to the grocery store confirms that a 4-pack 
of 8.5~W General Electric LED bulbs retails for \$6,
or \$1.50 each.
The LED bulbs provide as much illumination as 60~W incandescents and
are claimed to save \$84 of \$0.11/kW-hr electricity over their 13.6~year lifetime,
if they are used 3 hours/day.
Thus, the expected lifetime device-level energy savings are $E_{sav,dev,expected}$ = 763.6~kW-hr.
From Eq.~\ref{eq:P_eqn}, the unit profit~($P$) from the LED bulb is expected to be 
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:profit}
  P = \frac{\$\Sexpr{p_E_f}}{\mathrm{\kWhr}} 
            - \frac{\$\Sexpr{format(C_install, digits = 3, nsmall = 2)}}{(1 - \Sexpr{Re_dev}) 
                \times \Sexpr{format(E_sav_dev_expected, digits = 4)} \; \mathrm{\kWhr}} 
            = \Sexpr{format(P, digits = 4)} \; \$/\mathrm{\kWhr} \; .
\end{equation}


%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Economy-wide rebound}
\label{sec:economy_wide_rebound}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

<<Re_EW>>= 
Re_EW_func <- function(MPC = NULL, k = 1 / (1 - MPC), I_E_p = NULL, p_E_f = NULL,
                       C_install = NULL, E_sav_dev_expected = NULL, Re_dev, 
                       P = p_E_f - C_install / ((1 - Re_dev) * E_sav_dev_expected), 
                       kIP = k * I_E_p * P){
  Re_EW <- 1 - (1 - kIP) * (1 - Re_dev)
  return(Re_EW)
}
kIProfit <- k * I_E_p * P
Re_EW <- Re_EW_func(kIP = kIProfit, Re_dev = Re_dev)
kIprice <- k * I_E_p * p_E_f
dReEW_dRedev <- 1 - kIprice
@ 

The economy-wide rebound for the case study can be calculated by Eq.~\ref{eq:Re_EW}, 
beginning with the value of $k I_{E_p} P$:
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:kIP}
  k I_{E_p} P = \Sexpr{format(k, digits = 4)} 
                  \times \Sexpr{format(I_E_p, digits = 4)} \frac{\mathrm{\kWhr}}{\$} 
                  \times \Sexpr{format(P, digits = 4, nsmall = 4)} \frac{\$}{\mathrm{\kWhr}}
                  = \Sexpr{format(kIProfit, digits = 4)} \; ,
\end{equation}
%
followed by calculation of $Re_{EW}$:
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:Re_EW_val}
  Re_{EW} = 1 - (1 - k I_{E_p} P) (1 - Re_{dev}) 
          = 1 - (1 - \Sexpr{format(kIProfit, digits = 4)})(1 - \Sexpr{format(Re_dev, digits = 4)})
          = \Sexpr{format(Re_EW, digits = 4)} \; .
\end{equation}

Finally, the first derivative of economy-wide rebound with respect to device-level rebound 
can be calculated using Eq.~\ref{eq:dRe_EW/dRe_dev}:
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:dRe_EW/dRe_dev_val}
  \frac{\mathrm{d} Re_{EW}}{\mathrm{d} Re_{dev}} = 1 - k I_{E_p} p_{E_f}
                                                  = 1 - \Sexpr{format(kIprice, digits = 5)}
                                                  = \Sexpr{format(dReEW_dRedev, digits = 4)} \; .
\end{equation}
%


