As time progresses, most countries are becoming \emph{less} energy intensive
($I_{E_p}$ is getting smaller).
The effective price of energy has \emph{declined} over the past century
($p_{E_f}$ is going down).
All other things being equal, the above trends would tend to decrease $Re_{EW}$.
Thus, backfire is likely becoming smaller.
And energy-efficiency-driven, backfire-enabled economic growth could be stalling.
In other words, conditions for backfire were more favorable 100 years ago.


